    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-11-24T21:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-11-24T21:00:00-05:00" n="744"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d744">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">893.796/275: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Counselor of Embassy in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Peck</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Chungking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-11-25T09:00:00+07:00"
                            >November 25, 1939—9 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received November 25—3:05 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>608. F. B. Lynch, recent adviser to the Ministry of Finance, informed Weil<note
                        n="84" xml:id="d744fn84">T. Eliot Weil, Third Secretary of Embassy in
                        China.</note> November 23 that the first flight on the Chungking–Hami Air
                    Line has been scheduled tentatively for December 4; that Junkers planes owned by
                    Eurasia but operated by the Ministry of Communications and piloted by Chinese
                    will fly to Hami via Sian and Lanchow; and that Russian-built DC3’s will be used
                    between Hami and Alma Alta, where the line will presumably connect with a line
                    to Moscow. Inauguration of the Hami–Alma Alta Line has not yet been
                    announced.</p>
                <p>Lynch is being sent to the northwest to investigate movements of cargo under
                    Sino-Russian barter agreements. It appears that the Chinese Government suspects
                    that Chinese products—particularly wool—which might be sent to Russia are
                    finding their way into Japanese hands.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Peiping, Shanghai.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Peck</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
